princomp

princomp() performs a principal components analysis on the given numeric data matrix and returns the results as an object of class princomp.

pca12 <- princomp(mtcars)
screeplot(pca12)

library(factoextra)
var12 <- get_pca_var(pca12)
var12
## Principal Component Analysis Results for variables
##  ===================================================
##   Name       Description                                    
## 1 "$coord"   "Coordinates for the variables"                
## 2 "$cor"     "Correlations between variables and dimensions"
## 3 "$cos2"    "Cos2 for the variables"                       
## 4 "$contrib" "contributions of the variables"
install.packages("corrplot", repos = "http://cran.us.r-project.org")

ggbiplot from Data Camp

`ggbiplot() lelt us draw biplot by using ggplot. I will illustrate the mtcars pca with ggbiplot.

install.packages("devtools", repos = "http://cran.us.r-project.org")
## 
## The downloaded binary packages are in
##  /var/folders/w0/drzb7gkj3q10skqwfg6kswk80000gn/T//RtmpCDMcOk/downloaded_packages
library(devtools)
install_github("vqv/ggbiplot")
library(ggbiplot)
mtcars.pca <- prcomp(mtcars[,c(2:8,10,11)], center = TRUE,scale. = TRUE)
ggbiplot(mtcars.pca)

mtcars.pca <- prcomp(mtcars[,c(2:8,10,11)], center = TRUE,scale. = TRUE)
ggbiplot(mtcars.pca)

The folowing code chunk is from Data Camp Tutorial of PCA. (https://www.datacamp.com/community/tutorials/pca-analysis-r) I only copied these codes to see how the ggbiplot with ellipse look like, because this is my very first time to see/use plot with ellipses like this.

mtcars.country <- c(rep("Japan", 3), rep("US",4), rep("Europe", 7), rep("US",3), "Europe", rep("Japan", 3), rep("US",4), rep("Europe", 3), "US", rep("Europe", 3))
ggbiplot(mtcars.pca, ellipse = TRUE,  labels = rownames(mtcars), groups = mtcars.country)
